  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Papilloma: the benign culprit of bloody nipple drip.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Intraductal papilloma. This is the most common cause of *pathologic* nipple discharge, which is typically spontaneous, unilateral, and from a single duct. While often benign, it warrants thorough investigation to rule out malignancy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntraductal papillomas are benign epithelial tumors that grow within the lactiferous ducts, usually close to the nipple. Their friable nature makes them prone to bleeding, leading to serous or bloody nipple discharge. The discharge is often spontaneous and originates from a single duct, making it a classic presentation for this condition. Surgical excision of the involved duct is often diagnostic and therapeutic.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Prolactinoma) (Incorrect): Prolactinoma causes galactorrhea, which is milky discharge, not typically serous or bloody pathologic discharge.\nOption B (Hypothyroidism) (Incorrect): Hypothyroidism can cause galactorrhea due to increased TRH stimulating prolactin, but it is a less common cause than prolactinoma and does not typically present as pathologic discharge.\nOption C (breast cancer) (Incorrect): While breast cancer is a critical cause to rule out, it is responsible for a smaller percentage of nipple discharge cases (5-15%) compared to intraductal papilloma, which is the most common benign cause.\nOption D (Fibrocystic disease with ductalectasia) (Incorrect): Fibrocystic changes and duct ectasia can cause nipple discharge, but it is often bilateral, multi-ductal, and less frequently spontaneous or bloody compared to discharge from an intraductal papilloma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Physiologic Discharge | Pathologic Discharge |\n|---|---|---|\n| Character | Milky, multi-colored, sticky | Serous, bloody, clear, watery |\n| Laterality | Bilateral | Unilateral |\n| Ducts | Multi-ductal | Single-duct |\n| Spontaneity | Expressed | Spontaneous |\n| Common Causes | Prolactinoma, medications, hypothyroidism | Intraductal papilloma, cancer, duct ectasia |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unilateral, spontaneous, single-duct nipple discharge? Think papilloma first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nMammography and ultrasound are initial imaging modalities. Ductography (galactography) can be performed to visualize the ductal system and identify filling defects or masses within the duct, characteristic of a papilloma. Intraoperatively, microdochectomy (excision of the affected duct) is performed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Breast Surgeons (ASBS) Consensus Guideline on the Management of Benign Breast Disease (2018) recommends evaluation of pathologic nipple discharge.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Prolactinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hypothyroidism | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | breast cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Fibrocystic disease with ductalectasia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Intraductal papilloma | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) The most common cause of galactorrhea is a tumor in the pituitary gland.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
