  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pancreatitis's most common 'pseudo' problem is real.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Pseudocyst. This verdict is accurate because pseudocysts are the most frequently encountered local complication following an episode of acute pancreatitis, often developing weeks after the initial inflammatory insult.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute pancreatitis involves inflammation and potential autodigestion of the pancreatic tissue. When pancreatic fluid, inflammatory exudate, and necrotic debris accumulate and become walled off by a fibrous capsule, typically after 4-6 weeks, a pseudocyst forms. This encapsulation distinguishes it from an acute peripancreatic fluid collection. Its relatively high incidence compared to other severe local complications, such as abscess or necrosis, makes it the most common serious sequela, often requiring intervention if symptomatic or growing.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Abscess): Incorrect. Pancreatic abscesses are less common than pseudocysts and represent a secondary infection of necrotic pancreatic or peripancreatic tissue, typically a more severe and later complication.\nOption C (Bowel obstruction): Incorrect. While severe acute pancreatitis can cause an adynamic ileus (functional obstruction) due to inflammation, a true mechanical bowel obstruction is not a common direct complication of the pancreatitis itself.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Description | Timing | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Acute Peripancreatic Fluid Collection (APFC) | Homogeneous fluid collection, no wall | Early (<4 weeks) | Conservative |\n| Pancreatic Pseudocyst | Walled-off fluid collection, no solid component | Late (>4 weeks) | Observation, drainage if symptomatic |\n| Acute Necrotic Collection (ANC) | Heterogeneous collection with solid/liquid components | Early (<4 weeks) | Conservative, step-up approach if infected |\n| Walled-off Necrosis (WON) | Encapsulated necrotic collection | Late (>4 weeks) | Observation, drainage if symptomatic/infected |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pseudocyst is the most common local complication of acute pancreatitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a contrast-enhanced CT scan, a pseudocyst typically appears as a well-defined, encapsulated, usually unilocular fluid collection adjacent to the pancreas, often with a smooth, enhancing wall.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guideline: Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2013, updated 2018). It recommends imaging for persistent symptoms or complications like pseudocysts.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Abscess | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pseudocyst | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Bowel obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
