  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Feed the gut, spare the pancreas!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Naso-jejunal tube. In acute pancreatitis, early nutritional support is crucial, and enteral nutrition is preferred over parenteral nutrition. A naso-jejunal tube allows for feeding distal to the inflamed pancreas, minimizing pancreatic stimulation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute pancreatitis involves inflammation of the pancreas, and stimulating pancreatic enzyme secretion can worsen the condition. Enteral nutrition delivered via a naso-jejunal tube bypasses the stomach and duodenum, directly delivering nutrients into the jejunum. This approach minimizes pancreatic stimulation while providing essential nutritional support, which is vital for gut barrier integrity and overall recovery. Studies have shown that early enteral nutrition reduces infectious complications and mortality compared to total parenteral nutrition (TPN) in severe acute pancreatitis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (TPN) (Incorrect): Total Parenteral Nutrition (TPN) is associated with higher risks of infection, gut atrophy, and is generally reserved for cases where enteral nutrition is not feasible or contraindicated. Enteral nutrition is the preferred route.\nOption B (Regular diet with low sugar) (Incorrect): Oral feeding, even a modified diet, is contraindicated in the acute phase of severe pancreatitis as it stimulates pancreatic enzyme secretion and can exacerbate inflammation.\nOption C (High protein, high ca, low sugar) (Incorrect): Similar to option B, any oral diet is generally contraindicated in the acute phase of severe pancreatitis. The specific macronutrient composition is secondary to the route of administration.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nutrition Type | Route | Indication/Benefit | Drawbacks/Considerations |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Oral Diet | Oral | Mild pancreatitis, once pain resolves and labs improve | Contraindicated in severe acute phase, stimulates pancreas |\n| Naso-jejunal tube (Enteral) | Jejunal | Moderate to severe pancreatitis, preferred over TPN | Requires tube placement, risk of dislodgement |\n| TPN (Parenteral) | IV | Enteral nutrition not feasible/contraindicated (e.g., ileus, bowel ischemia) | Higher infection risk, gut atrophy, more expensive |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: \"Enteral nutrition via NJ tube is gold standard for severe pancreatitis.\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, you might see pancreatic edema, necrosis, or fluid collections. For naso-jejunal tube placement, fluoroscopy or endoscopy is often used to confirm the correct position of the tube in the jejunum.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guideline: Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2013). Recommends that enteral nutrition is preferred over parenteral nutrition in patients with severe acute pancreatitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | TPN | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Regular diet with low sugar | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | High protein ,high ca , low sugar | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Naso-jujenal tube | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
