  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Flank or umbilical ecchymosis means pancreatic bleed, not just inflammation.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nAcute pancreatitis is the correct diagnosis. The combination of right upper quadrant pain radiating to the back, nausea, and vomiting, along with the pathognomonic Grey-Turner's and Cullen's signs, strongly indicates severe acute pancreatitis with retroperitoneal hemorrhage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute pancreatitis involves inflammation and autodigestion of the pancreas. In severe cases, this can lead to necrosis and hemorrhage. Grey-Turner's sign (ecchymosis of the flanks) and Cullen's sign (periumbilical ecchymosis) are clinical manifestations of retroperitoneal bleeding, where activated pancreatic enzymes erode blood vessels, allowing blood to track along fascial planes to the skin. The retroperitoneal location of the pancreas explains the characteristic back pain radiation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Acute cholecystitis) (Incorrect): While acute cholecystitis presents with RUQ pain, nausea, and vomiting, the pain typically radiates to the right shoulder or scapula, not the back. Crucially, Grey-Turner's and Cullen's signs are specific indicators of retroperitoneal hemorrhage, which is not a feature of acute cholecystitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Pancreatitis | Acute Cholecystitis |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pain Location/Radiation | Epigastric/RUQ, radiates to back | RUQ, radiates to right shoulder/scapula |\n| Classic Signs | Grey-Turner's, Cullen's | Murphy's sign |\n| Etiology | Gallstones, alcohol, hypertriglyceridemia | Gallstones obstructing cystic duct |\n| Lab Markers | Elevated amylase/lipase | Elevated WBC, mild LFTs, normal amylase/lipase |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Grey-Turner's and Cullen's signs scream hemorrhagic pancreatitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, you would see pancreatic edema, peripancreatic fat stranding, fluid collections, and potentially areas of necrosis or hemorrhage. In severe cases, retroperitoneal blood tracking could be visualized.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guideline: Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2013, updated 2018). It recommends early aggressive intravenous hydration, pain control, and identification/treatment of the underlying etiology. CT scan is indicated for severe cases or when the diagnosis is uncertain.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Acute pancreatitis | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Acute chlocystitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
