  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the belly screams \"ouch\" in the RLQ, think appendix!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. The most diagnostic clinical finding for appendicitis is localized tenderness with rebound in the right lower quadrant, indicating peritoneal irritation directly over the inflamed appendix. This physical sign is crucial for guiding diagnosis and management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAppendicitis typically begins with luminal obstruction, leading to distension, bacterial overgrowth, and inflammation. As the inflammation progresses, it irritates the parietal peritoneum, causing localized pain. Rebound tenderness, specifically, signifies peritoneal inflammation, where the rapid release of pressure causes more pain than the initial compression, localizing the inflammatory process to the right lower quadrant (McBurney's point). This direct physical sign is highly indicative of the underlying pathology and often prompts further investigation or surgical intervention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Fever) (Incorrect): Fever is a systemic sign of inflammation and infection, but it is non-specific and often a later finding in appendicitis. Many other conditions can cause fever.\nOption B (Diarrhea) (Incorrect): Diarrhea is an atypical symptom of appendicitis, more commonly associated with gastroenteritis or other colonic pathologies. While some patients may experience altered bowel habits, it's not a primary diagnostic feature.\nOption C (Urinary symptoms) (Incorrect): Urinary symptoms (e.g., dysuria, frequency) can occur if an inflamed appendix lies close to the bladder or ureter, causing referred irritation. However, these are not direct signs of appendiceal inflammation and are more suggestive of a urinary tract infection.\nOption D (Leukocytosis) (Incorrect): Leukocytosis (elevated white blood cell count) is a general indicator of inflammation or infection. While common in appendicitis, it is non-specific and can be seen in numerous other conditions, making it less diagnostic than localized physical findings.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Appendicitis (Classic) | Gastroenteritis | UTI |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Pain Location** | RLQ, often migratory from periumbilical | Diffuse abdominal, cramping | Suprapubic, flank |\n| **Rebound Tenderness** | Present, localized RLQ | Absent or diffuse, mild | Absent |\n| **Fever** | Common, usually low-grade | Variable, can be high | Common, can be high |\n| **Leukocytosis** | Common | Variable | Common |\n| **Bowel Habits** | Anorexia, constipation (sometimes diarrhea) | Diarrhea, vomiting | Normal |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: RLQ tenderness with rebound is the hallmark of peritoneal irritation in appendicitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, a dilated appendix (>6mm diameter), wall thickening, periappendiceal fat stranding, and sometimes an appendicolith are seen. Intraoperatively, the appendix will appear erythematous, edematous, and potentially purulent, with surrounding inflammatory exudate.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Acute Appendicitis in Adults and Children (2020). Recommends clinical evaluation combined with imaging (ultrasound or CT) for diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Fever | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Diarrhea | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Urinary symptoms | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Leukocytosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Tender right lower quadrant with rebound | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
