  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Morphine makes the gallbladder groan, not go.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Morphine. Morphine is often considered contraindicated or used with caution in acute cholecystitis due to its potential to cause spasm of the Sphincter of Oddi, which could theoretically worsen biliary obstruction and pain.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute cholecystitis involves inflammation of the gallbladder, often due to obstruction of the cystic duct by a gallstone. Pain relief is crucial. Morphine, an opioid analgesic, acts on mu-opioid receptors. These receptors are present in the smooth muscle of the Sphincter of Oddi. Activation of these receptors can lead to contraction and spasm of the sphincter, potentially increasing intraductal pressure and exacerbating the obstruction and pain associated with acute cholecystitis. While the clinical significance of this spasm is debated, it remains a classic teaching point and a reason for caution or contraindication in some guidelines.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Naproxen (an NSAID) is often used for pain relief in acute cholecystitis. NSAIDs reduce inflammation and can be effective in managing the pain associated with the condition, and are not contraindicated.\nOption B (Incorrect): Acetaminophen is a non-opioid analgesic commonly used for pain management. It does not have the same effect on the Sphincter of Oddi as morphine and is not contraindicated in acute cholecystitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Analgesic Type | Mechanism of Action | Use in Acute Cholecystitis | Contraindications/Cautions |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| NSAIDs (e.g., Naproxen, Ketorolac) | Prostaglandin synthesis inhibition, anti-inflammatory | First-line for pain and inflammation | Renal impairment, GI bleeding risk |\n| Acetaminophen | Central analgesic, antipyretic | Adjunct for pain relief | Liver disease (high doses) |\n| Opioids (e.g., Morphine) | Mu-opioid receptor agonist | For severe pain, if NSAIDs insufficient | Potential Sphincter of Oddi spasm (classic teaching) |\n| Opioids (e.g., Fentanyl, Meperidine) | Mu-opioid receptor agonist | Alternatives to morphine, less Sphincter of Oddi spasm (Meperidine has other issues) | Respiratory depression, sedation, Meperidine neurotoxicity |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Avoid morphine in cholecystitis due to Sphincter of Oddi spasm.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, acute cholecystitis typically shows gallbladder wall thickening (>3mm), pericholecystic fluid, and a positive sonographic Murphy's sign. No specific imaging finding directly relates to morphine's effect on the Sphincter of Oddi, but the overall picture of obstruction would be present.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018 for the management of acute cholecystitis. These guidelines recommend NSAIDs as the first-line analgesic for acute cholecystitis, with opioids reserved for severe pain, acknowledging the historical concern regarding Sphincter of Oddi spasm with morphine but not strictly contraindicating it in all cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Naproxen | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Acetaminophen | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Morphine | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
