  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When no stones are found, think critical illness and high mortality.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nAcalculous cholecystitis is a severe inflammatory condition of the gallbladder that occurs in the absence of gallstones. It is predominantly seen in critically ill patients, often as a complication of major trauma, burns, sepsis, or extensive surgical procedures.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe pathophysiology of acalculous cholecystitis in critically ill patients is multifactorial. Prolonged fasting, total parenteral nutrition (TPN), and opioid use can lead to gallbladder stasis. This stasis, combined with systemic inflammation, ischemia, and reperfusion injury common in critical illness, results in mucosal damage, increased bile viscosity, and ultimately, acute inflammation of the gallbladder wall, even without the presence of stones.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Acalculous cholecystitis is defined by the absence of gallstones. While common bile duct stones cause choledocholithiasis, they are not typically associated with acalculous cholecystitis itself.\nOption B (Incorrect): Acalculous cholecystitis accounts for 5-10% of all acute cholecystitis cases, not less than 1%.\nOption C (Incorrect): Acalculous cholecystitis carries a significantly higher morbidity and mortality (up to 30-50%) compared to calculous cholecystitis due to its association with critical illness and patient comorbidities.\nOption E (Incorrect): A HIDA scan in acute cholecystitis (including acalculous) typically shows non-filling of the gallbladder due to cystic duct obstruction or severe inflammation, not filling.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Calculous Cholecystitis | Acalculous Cholecystitis |\n|---|---|---|\n| Etiology | Gallstones obstructing cystic duct | Gallbladder stasis, ischemia, critical illness (trauma, sepsis, burns, surgery) |\n| Patient Population | Generally healthier, often ambulatory | Critically ill, often intubated or post-op |\n| Diagnosis | RUQ pain, fever, leukocytosis, ultrasound showing stones/wall thickening | Fever, leukocytosis, RUQ tenderness (if conscious), ultrasound showing wall thickening/pericholecystic fluid, HIDA non-filling |\n| Prognosis | Good with cholecystectomy (mortality 1-4%) | Poor, high morbidity/mortality (up to 30-50%) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acalculous cholecystitis: no stones, high stakes, critical illness.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, you would typically see gallbladder wall thickening (>3-4mm), pericholecystic fluid, and potentially a positive sonographic Murphy's sign (if the patient is conscious). A HIDA scan would show non-visualization of the gallbladder. Intraoperatively, the gallbladder may appear distended, edematous, and inflamed, often without palpable stones.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018: Management Bundles for Acute Cholangitis and Cholecystitis. These guidelines provide diagnostic criteria and management strategies for acute cholecystitis, including specific considerations for acalculous cholecystitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It is usually associated with stones in the common bile duct. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It occurs in less than 1% of cases of cholecystitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | It has a more favorable prognosis than calculouscholecystitis. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | It occurs after trauma or operation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | HIDA scan shows filling gallbladder | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
