  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Fiber: Your first defense against the dreaded 'roids!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A. For a patient presenting with an asymptomatic, non-prolapsing, non-thrombosed internal hemorrhoid (Grade I), the primary management is conservative, focusing on dietary modifications to improve bowel habits.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIncreasing dietary fiber is the cornerstone of conservative management for early-stage hemorrhoids. Fiber adds bulk to stool, making it softer and easier to pass, thereby reducing straining during defecation. This reduction in straining decreases pressure on the hemorrhoidal cushions, preventing their engorgement, prolapse, and potential thrombosis, thus alleviating symptoms and preventing progression.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): While laxatives can be used to soften stool, increasing dietary fiber is generally the first-line and most natural approach. Laxatives may be considered if fiber alone is insufficient or for acute constipation, but they are not the primary initial management for asymptomatic Grade I hemorrhoids.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hemorrhoidectomy is a surgical procedure reserved for symptomatic, higher-grade hemorrhoids (typically Grade III or IV) that have failed conservative or office-based treatments. It is an overly aggressive and inappropriate intervention for an asymptomatic, non-prolapsing Grade I hemorrhoid.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hemorrhoid Grade | Description | Typical Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| Grade I | Internal, no prolapse, may bleed | Conservative (fiber, fluids, lifestyle) |\n| Grade II | Prolapses with defecation, reduces spontaneously | Conservative, office-based procedures (banding, sclerotherapy) |\n| Grade III | Prolapses with defecation, requires manual reduction | Office-based procedures, surgical hemorrhoidectomy |\n| Grade IV | Prolapsed and irreducible | Surgical hemorrhoidectomy |\n| Thrombosed External | Acute painful swelling | Excision of thrombus, conservative (sitz baths, analgesics) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Grade I hemorrhoids: fiber first, surgery never.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn anoscopy, internal hemorrhoids appear as vascular cushions above the dentate line. In Grade I, they are visible but do not prolapse outside the anal canal.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Hemorrhoids (2018). These guidelines recommend conservative management, including dietary fiber and fluid intake, as the initial treatment for Grade I and II hemorrhoids.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Increase fiber diet | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Give laxative | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Do hemorroidectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
