  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't dismiss the drip; hemorrhoids are the most common culprit.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nHemorrhoids are the most common cause of chronic, interrupted rectal bleeding. This is due to their high prevalence in the general population and the friable nature of the vascular cushions in the anal canal.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHemorrhoids are normal vascular cushions located in the anal canal. When these cushions become engorged, prolapsed, or traumatized by the passage of stool, their thin-walled vessels can rupture, leading to bleeding. This bleeding is typically bright red, painless, occurs with defecation, and is characteristically intermittent, often presenting as spotting on toilet paper or dripping into the toilet bowl.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Diverticulosis) (Incorrect): While diverticulosis is a common cause of lower gastrointestinal bleeding, it typically presents as acute, painless, and often large-volume bleeding, rather than chronic, intermittent, or small-volume rectal bleeding.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hemorrhoids | Diverticulosis |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Bleeding Character** | Chronic, intermittent, bright red, small volume, often with defecation | Acute, painless, large volume, often self-limiting |\n| **Associated Symptoms** | Pruritus, pain (if thrombosed), prolapse | Usually asymptomatic until bleeding or inflammation |\n| **Typical Age Group** | Any age, common in young to middle-aged adults | Older adults (>60 years) |\n| **Location of Bleeding** | Anorectal junction | Colon (often right-sided for bleeding) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For chronic, intermittent rectal bleeding, always think hemorrhoids first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn anoscopy or colonoscopy, hemorrhoids appear as engorged, often prolapsing, vascular cushions in the anal canal, which may show signs of recent bleeding or friability.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Hemorrhoids (2018). These guidelines confirm hemorrhoids as a primary cause of rectal bleeding and outline diagnostic and treatment strategies.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Diverticulosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hemorrhoids | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
