  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Face heals fast, pull sutures faster.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe ideal time for facial suture removal is between 4-7 days, making 3 to 5 days the closest and most appropriate option among the choices. This timing is critical to balance adequate wound healing with minimizing cosmetic sequelae.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe face boasts an exceptionally rich vascular supply, which significantly accelerates the wound healing process compared to other body regions. This rapid healing allows for earlier suture removal, typically before 7 days, to prevent the formation of 'railroad track' or 'suture track' marks. These marks occur when epithelial cells migrate down the suture tract, creating permanent indentations. Early removal minimizes the foreign body reaction and reduces the risk of hypertrophic scarring, ensuring optimal cosmetic outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Absorbable sutures are generally not recommended for superficial skin closure on the face due to their higher tissue reactivity, which can lead to increased inflammation, a more prominent scar, and the potential for 'spitting' sutures. Non-absorbable sutures are preferred for precise skin approximation.\nOption C (Incorrect): Two weeks is far too long for facial sutures. Leaving sutures in for this duration significantly increases the risk of permanent suture marks, hyperpigmentation, and an unfavorable cosmetic outcome due to epithelialization into the suture tracts and prolonged foreign body reaction.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Body Area | Suture Removal Time | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Face/Neck | 3-7 days | Excellent vascularity, minimize track marks |\n| Scalp | 7-10 days | Good vascularity, hair coverage |\n| Trunk/Extremities | 7-14 days | Moderate vascularity, higher tension |\n| Joints/Back | 10-21 days | High tension, slower healing |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Facial sutures out early, scar prevention is key.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, ensure meticulous, low-tension closure of facial wounds to facilitate early suture removal and achieve superior cosmetic results. Avoid excessive tension on skin edges.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Plastic Surgeons (ASPS) recommendations for facial wound closure and care emphasize early suture removal for optimal cosmetic outcomes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | U should use absorbable suture | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 3 to 5 Days | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 2 weeks | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) The ideal is between 4-7 days.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
