  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the right side hurts, ultrasound's your first port.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that an ultrasound of the upper abdomen is the next appropriate investigation. This is because the patient's symptoms of right hypochondrial pain, especially increasing with respiration (suggesting diaphragmatic irritation), and tenderness are highly suggestive of acute cholecystitis or biliary colic, for which ultrasound is the gold standard initial diagnostic tool.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUltrasound of the upper abdomen is the preferred initial imaging modality for suspected gallbladder pathology due to its non-invasive nature, lack of radiation exposure, and high sensitivity and specificity for gallstones and signs of inflammation. It can readily identify cholelithiasis, gallbladder wall thickening (>3mm), pericholecystic fluid, and a sonographic Murphy's sign, which are key diagnostic criteria for acute cholecystitis. Furthermore, it can assess the common bile duct for dilation and identify other potential causes of right upper quadrant pain, making it a comprehensive first-line investigation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (X-ray) (Incorrect): An X-ray of the abdomen has very limited utility in diagnosing gallbladder pathology as only about 10-15% of gallstones are radiopaque. It is not sensitive enough to detect inflammation or other signs of cholecystitis.\nOption C (CT) (Incorrect): While CT can identify gallstones and signs of inflammation, it exposes the patient to radiation and is generally less sensitive than ultrasound for detecting gallstones and early inflammatory changes of the gallbladder. It is typically reserved for cases where ultrasound is inconclusive or when complications or alternative diagnoses are suspected.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Imaging Modality | Primary Indication | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Ultrasound (US)** | Suspected cholelithiasis, cholecystitis, biliary obstruction | Non-invasive, no radiation, high sensitivity for stones/inflammation, real-time | Operator dependent, limited by bowel gas/obesity |\n| **CT Scan** | Complications of cholecystitis, alternative diagnoses, pancreatitis | Good for surrounding structures, complications, alternative diagnoses | Radiation exposure, less sensitive for small stones/early inflammation |\n| **X-ray Abdomen** | Bowel obstruction, perforation, renal stones (radiopaque) | Quick, widely available | Poor for soft tissue, low sensitivity for gallbladder pathology |\n| **HIDA Scan** | Acalculous cholecystitis, cystic duct obstruction | Functional assessment of gallbladder, high specificity for acute cholecystitis | Radiation exposure, takes longer, less anatomical detail than US/CT |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: RUQ pain? US first, always for gallbladder.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, you would look for gallstones (hyperechoic foci with posterior shadowing), gallbladder wall thickening (>3mm), pericholecystic fluid, and a positive sonographic Murphy's sign (pain elicited by transducer pressure over the gallbladder).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Tokyo Guidelines 2018 for the management of acute cholecystitis recommend abdominal ultrasound as the initial imaging modality for diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | X-ray | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | US of upper abdomen | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | CT | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
