  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it's cystic and on the labia, think Bartholin!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct diagnosis for a healthy female presenting with an acute-onset, non-tender, 3 cm cystic mass on her labia is a Bartholin cyst. This presentation perfectly aligns with the typical characteristics of an obstructed Bartholin gland duct.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBartholin glands are paired glands located at the posterior-lateral aspect of the vaginal opening, within the labia majora. Their ducts can become obstructed, leading to the accumulation of mucus and the formation of a cyst. These cysts are typically non-tender unless they become infected, forming an abscess. The acute onset of a non-tender, cystic mass in this specific location is highly characteristic of a Bartholin cyst, making it the most likely diagnosis among the given options.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Vaginal adenosis) (Incorrect): This is a condition where glandular tissue is present in the vagina, typically asymptomatic or causing discharge, not presenting as an acute, palpable cystic mass on the labia.\nOption C (\"Schic cyst\") (Incorrect): This term is likely a typo. If referring to a Skene's gland cyst, it would be located near the urethra, not on the labia. If referring to a Gartner's duct cyst, it would be along the lateral vaginal wall. Neither fits the described location on the labia. A sebaceous cyst, while possible on the labia, typically has a slower growth pattern and may have a punctum, making acute onset less typical.\nOption D (Hygroma) (Incorrect): A cystic hygroma is a congenital lymphatic malformation, usually found in the neck or axilla, and would not present as an acute-onset lesion on the labia in an adult.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Bartholin Cyst | Skene's Gland Cyst | Gartner's Duct Cyst | Sebaceous Cyst |\n| :---------------- | :------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------- |\n| **Location** | Posterior-lateral aspect of vaginal introitus (labia majora) | Periurethral (anterior vaginal wall) | Lateral vaginal wall | Anywhere on skin with sebaceous glands (e.g., labia majora) |\n| **Origin** | Obstruction of Bartholin gland duct | Obstruction of Skene's gland duct | Remnant of Wolffian (mesonephric) duct | Blocked sebaceous gland |\n| **Presentation** | Cystic, non-tender (unless infected), acute/subacute onset | Small, cystic, periurethral, often asymptomatic | Cystic, along lateral vaginal wall, often asymptomatic | Slow-growing, firm or cystic, often with punctum, usually non-tender |\n| **Key Differentiating Factor** | Location on labia, acute onset, non-tender | Location near urethra | Location along lateral vaginal wall | Slower growth, punctum, can be anywhere on skin |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Location, location, location is key for vulvovaginal cysts.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn physical exam, a Bartholin cyst presents as a soft, fluctuant, non-tender mass at the 4 or 8 o'clock position relative to the vaginal introitus. Ultrasound can confirm the cystic nature and rule out solid masses.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) Practice Bulletin No. 206 (2019): Management of Benign Vulvar Lesions. It recommends conservative management for asymptomatic Bartholin cysts and incision and drainage or marsupialization for symptomatic cysts or abscesses.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Bartholin cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Vaginal adenosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | schic cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | hygroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
