  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 IBD: It's more than just a gut feeling; it's a gut on fire!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E. Abdominal distention is less consistently a primary sign or symptom of Inflammatory Bowel Disease (IBD) compared to the other options, which are classic manifestations of chronic gastrointestinal inflammation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIBD, encompassing Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis, involves chronic inflammation of the GI tract. Mucosal ulceration and friability lead to bleeding per rectum and mucus in stool. Rectal inflammation often causes tenesmus, the feeling of incomplete defecation. Systemic inflammation, malabsorption, and increased metabolic demands frequently result in significant weight loss, making these core diagnostic and monitoring features of IBD.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Bleeding per rectum is a hallmark symptom, especially in ulcerative colitis, due to mucosal ulceration and friability.\nOption B (Incorrect): Feeling of incomplete defecation (tenesmus) is common, particularly with rectal involvement in IBD, due to inflammation and irritation.\nOption C (Incorrect): Mucus in stool is a frequent finding in IBD, resulting from mucosal inflammation and damage to the intestinal lining.\nOption D (Incorrect): Weight loss is a common systemic symptom in IBD, driven by malabsorption, decreased oral intake, and the catabolic effects of chronic inflammation.\nOption E (Correct): Abdominal distention, while it can occur with severe disease, obstruction, or toxic megacolon, is not as consistently or primarily a direct symptom of IBD itself compared to the other options, which are more direct manifestations of the inflammatory process.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Symptom/Sign | Ulcerative Colitis (UC) | Crohn's Disease (CD) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Bleeding per rectum | Common, often prominent | Less common, can occur with colonic involvement |\n| Tenesmus | Common, especially with proctitis | Can occur with rectal involvement |\n| Mucus in stool | Common | Can occur |\n| Weight Loss | Common, especially with extensive disease | Very common, often more severe due to malabsorption |\n| Abdominal Pain | Common, often cramping | Very common, can be severe |\n| Abdominal Distention | Less common as primary symptom, can indicate complications (e.g., toxic megacolon) | Less common as primary symptom, can indicate obstruction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Classic IBD symptoms are direct results of inflammation; distention often signals complications.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy (colonoscopy with ileoscopy) is crucial for diagnosis, showing mucosal inflammation, ulcerations, pseudopolyps, and strictures. Imaging like CT or MRI enterography can reveal transmural inflammation, fistulas, abscesses, and strictures, which may lead to distention.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guidelines for the Management of Ulcerative Colitis in Adults (2019) and Crohn's Disease in Adults (2018) provide comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis and treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | bleeding per rectum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | feeling of incomplete defecation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Mucus comes with stool | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Weight Loss | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Abdominal distention | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
