  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When skin speaks volumes, but the body stays silent, think lymphoma.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question presents images of multiple cutaneous lesions on a patient's hand, explicitly stating the absence of organomegaly or lymphadenopathy. This clinical scenario, particularly the exclusion of systemic signs, strongly points towards a diagnosis that primarily manifests in the skin.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLymphoma can present as primary cutaneous lymphoma, where the disease is confined to the skin at diagnosis, or as cutaneous involvement of systemic lymphoma. These skin manifestations are highly variable, including patches, plaques, nodules, and tumors, which can sometimes ulcerate or become necrotic, as suggested by the images. The key to this diagnosis is the absence of systemic symptoms like lymphadenopathy or organomegaly, which are characteristic of many other conditions, including mononucleosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Mononucleosis is a systemic viral infection typically characterized by fever, pharyngitis, and prominent lymphadenopathy and often splenomegaly. The question explicitly rules out 'organomegaly or Lymphadenopathy,' making mononucleosis an unlikely diagnosis. While a rash can occur in mononucleosis, it is usually maculopapular and not typically nodular or ulcerative as depicted.\nOption B (Correct): Lymphoma, particularly primary cutaneous lymphoma, can present with varied skin lesions (nodules, plaques, tumors) without initial systemic involvement. The images are consistent with such lesions, and the absence of organomegaly or lymphadenopathy supports a diagnosis where the skin is the primary or sole apparent site of disease.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Mononucleosis | Cutaneous Lymphoma |\n|---|---|---|\n| Primary Presentation | Fever, pharyngitis, lymphadenopathy, splenomegaly | Skin lesions (patches, plaques, nodules, tumors) |\n| Systemic Symptoms | Common (fatigue, malaise) | Often absent in primary cutaneous forms |\n| Lymphadenopathy/Organomegaly | Characteristic | Usually absent in primary cutaneous forms, may be present in systemic forms |\n| Skin Lesions | Maculopapular rash (less common) | Varied, often nodular, ulcerative, or plaque-like |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cutaneous lesions without systemic signs can be primary cutaneous lymphoma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThe images provided show multiple, reddish-purple, raised cutaneous lesions, some with central ulceration or crusting, primarily on the hand. A diagnostic skin biopsy of these lesions is paramount, revealing atypical lymphoid infiltrates. Further staging may involve imaging like CT scans to rule out occult systemic involvement, despite the initial clinical assessment.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Mycosis Fungoides and Sezary Syndrome (2023) or NCCN Guidelines for B-Cell Lymphomas (2023). These guidelines emphasize skin biopsy for diagnosis and comprehensive staging for cutaneous lymphomas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Mononucleosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lymphoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
