  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cancer is the king of calcium chaos in the hospital.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Cancer. Malignancy is the most frequent cause of hypercalcemia in hospitalized patients, often indicating advanced disease and requiring prompt management.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMalignancy-associated hypercalcemia (MAHC) accounts for approximately 90% of hypercalcemia cases in hospitalized patients. The primary mechanisms include humoral hypercalcemia of malignancy (HHM), typically mediated by parathyroid hormone-related protein (PTHrP) secreted by solid tumors, and osteolytic metastases, where tumor cells directly or indirectly stimulate osteoclast activity leading to bone destruction and calcium release. Less commonly, some lymphomas produce 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D (calcitriol), increasing intestinal calcium absorption.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Dietary, such as milk-alkali syndrome, is a less common cause of severe hypercalcemia requiring hospitalization compared to malignancy. It typically involves excessive calcium and alkali intake.\nOption B (Incorrect): Drug related, such as the use of thiazide diuretics, can cause mild hypercalcemia by increasing renal calcium reabsorption but rarely leads to severe hypercalcemia requiring hospitalization as the primary cause.\nOption C (Incorrect): Granulomatous disease (e.g., sarcoidosis, tuberculosis) can cause hypercalcemia due to unregulated production of 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D, but it is significantly less common than malignancy as a cause of hospitalized hypercalcemia.\nOption E (Incorrect): Dehydration can exacerbate hypercalcemia by reducing renal calcium excretion and increasing hemoconcentration, but it is rarely the primary underlying cause of significant hypercalcemia requiring hospitalization. It's often a consequence or contributing factor.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause of Hypercalcemia | Mechanism | Key Features |\n| :--------------------- | :-------- | :----------- |\n| Primary Hyperparathyroidism | Excess PTH from adenoma/hyperplasia | Elevated PTH, often mild/asymptomatic, outpatient |\n| Malignancy | PTHrP, osteolysis, calcitriol | Low/suppressed PTH, often severe, hospitalized |\n| Granulomatous Disease | Ectopic 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D | Low PTH, elevated 1,25-D, specific disease history |\n| Thiazide Diuretics | Increased renal Ca reabsorption | Mild hypercalcemia, history of diuretic use |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: When in the hospital, hypercalcemia often means cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (CT, MRI, PET scan) in patients with malignancy-associated hypercalcemia often reveals widespread osteolytic bone metastases or a primary tumor secreting PTHrP, even without overt bone involvement.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEndocrine Society Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Hypercalcemia of Malignancy (2016) recommends aggressive hydration and bisphosphonates as first-line treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Dietary, such as milk-alkali syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Drug related, such as the use of thiazide diuretics. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Granulomatous disease. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Dehydration. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
