  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Resuscitate, then patch the hole; save the soul.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption C is the best treatment for this critically ill patient with a perforated duodenal ulcer. The priority is aggressive resuscitation followed by the least invasive, yet effective, surgical source control.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe patient's presentation (febrile, semi-comatose, dehydrated, 3-day history) indicates severe sepsis and shock due to diffuse peritonitis from the perforated ulcer. Initial management must focus on resuscitation: NGT suction to decompress the stomach and prevent further spillage, aggressive rehydration to combat shock, and systemic antibiotics to treat sepsis. Once stabilized, the definitive treatment for a perforated duodenal ulcer, especially in a critically ill patient, is simple closure of the perforation, often using a Graham patch (omentopexy or plication). This procedure is quick, effective, and minimizes physiological stress compared to more extensive resections.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While resuscitation is correct, vagotomy and drainage is a more extensive procedure for definitive ulcer management and is not the primary treatment for perforation itself, especially in a septic, unstable patient. Simple closure is preferred.\nOption B (Incorrect): Observation is never appropriate for a perforated viscus. Surgical intervention is mandatory to close the perforation and prevent ongoing peritonitis and sepsis.\nOption D (Incorrect): Hemigastrectomy is a major, highly morbid procedure typically reserved for complicated ulcer disease (e.g., intractable bleeding, obstruction, malignancy) or very large perforations with tissue loss. It is far too aggressive and carries an unacceptably high risk for a 70-year-old, semi-comatose, septic patient with a perforated ulcer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Stable Patient (Early Presentation) | Unstable/Septic Patient (Late Presentation) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Initial Management | Resuscitation (fluids, AB), NGT | Aggressive Resuscitation (fluids, vasopressors, AB), NGT |\n| Surgical Approach | Laparoscopic or Open Graham Patch | Open Graham Patch (often preferred for speed/access) |\n| Adjunctive Procedures | H. pylori eradication, acid suppression | H. pylori eradication, acid suppression (post-op) |\n| Goal | Source control, definitive treatment | Source control, stabilize patient, minimize operative time |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Resuscitate, then simple closure (Graham patch) for perforated duodenal ulcer in critical patients.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain upright chest X-ray or CT scan, you would typically see free air under the diaphragm (pneumoperitoneum). Intraoperatively, a small perforation on the anterior duodenum would be identified, and a Graham patch would be performed by suturing a pedicle of omentum over the perforation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe World Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) guidelines for perforated peptic ulcer (2020) recommend prompt resuscitation and surgical closure (Graham patch) as the standard of care, especially in unstable patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Blood transfusion, Rehydrate, perform Vagotomy & drainage urgently. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | NGT suction, Rehydrate, systemic AB & observe. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | NGT suction, Rehydrate, systemic AB & perform Plication of the perforation. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Rehydrate, Blood transfusion, systemic AB & perform hemigastrectomy. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | none of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
