  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Meckel's in adults: Think twists and turns, not just blood.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption C, Intestinal obstruction, is the correct answer. In adults, intestinal obstruction is the most frequently encountered complication of Meckel's diverticulum, surpassing bleeding, diverticulitis, or perforation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMeckel's diverticulum, a remnant of the omphalomesenteric duct, can cause obstruction through various mechanisms. These include intussusception where the diverticulum acts as a lead point, volvulus of the small bowel around a fibrous band connecting the diverticulum to the umbilicus or mesentery, or incarceration within a hernia sac (Littre's hernia). The presence of heterotopic tissue, while often associated with bleeding, can also contribute to inflammation and subsequent obstruction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Bleeding) (Incorrect): While bleeding is the most common complication of Meckel's diverticulum in children, it is less common than obstruction in adults. Bleeding typically results from peptic ulceration caused by heterotopic gastric mucosa.\nOption B (Perforation) (Incorrect): Perforation is a less common complication, often occurring secondary to diverticulitis, ischemia, or foreign body impaction within the diverticulum. It is not the most common overall complication in adults.\nOption D (Ulceration) (Incorrect): Ulceration, usually due to heterotopic gastric mucosa, is the underlying cause of bleeding. While present, it is not the most common *complication* itself; rather, its sequelae (bleeding or perforation) are the complications, with obstruction being more prevalent in adults.\nOption E (Carcinoma) (Incorrect): Malignant transformation within a Meckel's diverticulum, such as adenocarcinoma or carcinoid, is exceedingly rare and certainly not the most common complication.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Children | Adults |\n|---|---|---|\n| Most Common Complication | Bleeding | Intestinal Obstruction |\n| Common Mechanisms | Peptic ulceration from heterotopic gastric mucosa leading to bleeding, intussusception | Volvulus around a fibrous band, intussusception, Littre's hernia, diverticulitis |\n| Clinical Presentation | Painless rectal bleeding, anemia | Abdominal pain, distension, vomiting, signs of obstruction |\n| Diagnostic Modality | Technetium-99m pertechnetate scan (Meckel's scan) | CT scan, small bowel series, laparoscopy/laparotomy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Adult Meckel's: Obstruction is the main attraction.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT scan), signs of small bowel obstruction such as dilated loops of small bowel with air-fluid levels would be seen. The Meckel's diverticulum itself might be visualized, especially if inflamed or acting as a lead point for intussusception. Intraoperatively, the diverticulum or its associated fibrous band would be identified as the cause of the obstruction, such as a volvulus around the band or the diverticulum acting as the apex of an intussusception.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWhile no single society guideline specifically addresses Meckel's diverticulum management, principles from the American College of Surgeons (ACS) and Society of American Gastrointestinal and Endoscopic Surgeons (SAGES) regarding small bowel obstruction and acute abdomen guide diagnosis and treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Bleeding | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Perforation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Intestinal obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Ulceration | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Carcinoma. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
