  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pancreatitis is a systemic disease; don't confuse its complications with surgical sequelae.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. Afferent loop syndrome is a complication of gastric surgery, specifically Billroth II gastrojejunostomy, and is not a direct complication of pancreatitis itself. The other options are well-recognized systemic or local complications of acute pancreatitis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute pancreatitis is a severe inflammatory process that can lead to both local and systemic complications. Local complications include pseudocyst, necrosis, and abscess formation. Systemic complications arise from the release of inflammatory mediators into the circulation, affecting distant organs such as the lungs (ARDS, atelectasis), kidneys (AKI), cardiovascular system (shock), and brain (encephalopathy/altered mental status). Sepsis is a critical complication, often stemming from infected pancreatic necrosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Pulmonary Atelectasis is a common pulmonary complication of severe pancreatitis due to diaphragmatic irritation, pleural effusions, and systemic inflammatory response leading to ARDS.\nOption B (Incorrect): Altered mental status can result from severe pancreatitis due to systemic inflammation, electrolyte imbalances, sepsis, or hypoxemia.\nOption C (Incorrect): Shock (hypovolemic, septic, or cardiogenic) is a life-threatening complication of severe pancreatitis due to fluid shifts, hemorrhage, or systemic inflammatory response syndrome (SIRS).\nOption E (Incorrect): Sepsis, particularly from infected pancreatic necrosis, is a major cause of morbidity and mortality in acute pancreatitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication Type | Example in Pancreatitis | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Pulmonary | Atelectasis, ARDS, Pleural Effusion | Inflammation affecting the diaphragm and lung parenchyma, leading to impaired gas exchange. |\n| Cardiovascular | Shock, Myocardial Depression | Systemic inflammatory response leading to vasodilation, fluid shifts, and myocardial dysfunction. |\n| Neurological | Altered Mental Status, Encephalopathy | Due to sepsis, electrolyte imbalances, hypoxemia, or direct inflammatory effects. |\n| Infectious | Sepsis, Infected Necrosis | Bacterial translocation or superinfection of necrotic pancreatic tissue. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pancreatitis complications are systemic; afferent loop syndrome is a surgical complication.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, pancreatitis complications like pleural effusions, ascites, pancreatic necrosis (non-enhancing areas), and pseudocysts are visible. Afferent loop syndrome would show a dilated, fluid-filled afferent limb proximal to an obstruction, typically in a patient with prior gastric surgery.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guideline: Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2013, updated 2018). Recommends early aggressive fluid resuscitation and identifies systemic complications as key determinants of severity.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pulmonary Atelectasis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Altered mental status | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Shock | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Afferent loop syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Sepsis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
