  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Sunburn is a classic first-degree burn.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 1st degree burn. This diagnosis is supported by the classic presentation of superficial epidermal injury: redness, pain, and intact capillary refill (reblanchable skin) without blistering.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFirst-degree burns, also known as superficial burns, involve only the epidermis. The characteristic redness is due to vasodilation in the superficial dermis, which is why the skin remains reblanchable. Pain is a prominent feature because nerve endings in the epidermis are irritated but not destroyed. This type of burn typically heals spontaneously within 3-6 days without scarring, as the basal layer of the epidermis remains intact to regenerate new skin.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): 2nd degree burns (partial thickness) would present with blisters in addition to redness, pain, and blanching, which are not mentioned in the patient's presentation.\nOption C (Incorrect): 3rd degree burns (full thickness) involve destruction of the entire dermis, leading to a leathery, white, or charred appearance, and often painless due to nerve damage, with no blanching. This does not match the description.\nOption D (Incorrect): \"Skin prodromal\" is not a recognized classification for burn depth or a specific skin condition in this context.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Burn Degree | Layers Involved | Appearance | Pain | Blanching | Blisters | Healing Time |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1st Degree | Epidermis | Red | Painful | Yes | No | 3-6 days |\n| 2nd Degree (Superficial Partial) | Epidermis, superficial dermis | Red, moist | Very painful | Yes | Yes | 1-3 weeks |\n| 2nd Degree (Deep Partial) | Epidermis, deep dermis | Red, white, dry | Less painful | Sluggish | Yes (ruptured) | 3-9 weeks |\n| 3rd Degree | Epidermis, dermis, subcutaneous tissue | White, leathery, charred | Painless | No | No | Requires grafting |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Red, painful, reblanchable skin without blisters = 1st degree burn.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNo specific imaging or intraoperative findings are typically associated with diagnosing 1st-degree burns; diagnosis is purely clinical.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Burn Association (ABA) Practice Guidelines for Burn Care (2018) recommends clinical assessment for burn depth classification.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 1st degree burn | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 2nd degree burn | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 3rd degree burn | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | skin prodromal | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
