  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cool water for burns, not butter or ice – keep it simple, keep it safe!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT: The correct answer is A, 'Wash by water with room temperature.' Immediate cooling with cool (not cold) water is the cornerstone of first aid for mild burns, effectively reducing pain, swelling, and the depth of injury.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nApplying cool water to a burn works by dissipating residual heat from the injured tissue, thereby limiting the progression of thermal damage. This immediate cooling also helps to reduce inflammation and provides significant pain relief by numbing nerve endings. The goal is to stop the burning process and minimize cellular injury, which is crucial in preventing the burn from deepening and improving healing outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Placing ice directly on a burn can cause vasoconstriction, leading to further tissue damage, frostbite, and potentially worsening the injury. It can also cause hypothermia in larger burns.\nOption C (Incorrect): Applying butter or other greasy substances is a harmful folk remedy. These substances can trap heat, promote bacterial growth, and make it more difficult for medical professionals to properly assess and clean the wound.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| First Aid Action | Rationale | Outcome |\n|---|---|---|\n| Cool/Room Temp Water | Dissipates heat, reduces pain & swelling | Prevents deepening, pain relief |\n| Ice | Causes vasoconstriction, frostbite | Worsens injury, tissue damage |\n| Butter/Grease | Traps heat, promotes infection | Increased pain, infection risk |\n| Sterile Dressing | Protects wound, prevents infection | Promotes healing, reduces contamination |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cool water is the immediate first step for burns; avoid ice and folk remedies.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNot applicable for this first aid question. No imaging or intraoperative findings are relevant.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Red Cross First Aid Guidelines (2020): Recommends cooling burns with cool or lukewarm running water for at least 10 minutes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Wash by water with room temperature | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Place an ice | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Put a butter | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
