  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When diverticulitis flares, antibiotics are your first line of defense!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is IV antibiotic. This patient presents with classic symptoms and imaging findings consistent with acute diverticulitis, which often requires immediate medical management including broad-spectrum intravenous antibiotics to cover enteric flora and prevent complications like abscess or perforation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute diverticulitis arises from inflammation or microperforation of a colonic diverticulum, typically in the sigmoid colon. The presence of fever and localized abdominal pain with imaging showing pericolic inflammation indicates an active infectious process. IV antibiotics target the bacterial overgrowth and translocation associated with diverticular inflammation, reducing systemic infection and local complications. This immediate intervention is crucial to stabilize the patient and prevent progression to more severe conditions requiring surgical intervention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Double contrast) (Incorrect): Double contrast barium enema is contraindicated in acute diverticulitis due to the risk of perforation and extravasation of contrast into the peritoneal cavity. It is typically used for elective evaluation of diverticular disease after the acute inflammatory process has resolved.\nOption C (Control diet) (Incorrect): While dietary modifications (e.g., low-residue diet during acute phase, high-fiber diet for prevention) are part of diverticulitis management, they are not the immediate \"next step\" for a patient presenting with fever and acute inflammation requiring urgent medical intervention.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Diverticulitis (Uncomplicated) | Acute Diverticulitis (Complicated) | Chronic Diverticular Disease |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Symptoms** | LLQ pain, fever, constipation/diarrhea | Severe pain, peritonitis, sepsis, mass | Intermittent LLQ pain, bloating, altered bowel habits |\n| **Imaging** | CT scan: wall thickening, fat stranding | CT scan: abscess, perforation, fistula, obstruction | Colonoscopy (after acute phase) |\n| **Treatment** | Oral/IV antibiotics, bowel rest, pain control | IV antibiotics, percutaneous drainage (abscess), surgery (perforation, obstruction) | High-fiber diet, lifestyle modification |\n| **Contraindications** | Colonoscopy, barium enema | Colonoscopy, barium enema | None (for colonoscopy/barium enema) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Fever + LLQ pain + fat stranding = IV antibiotics for acute diverticulitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, acute diverticulitis typically shows colonic wall thickening (>4mm), pericolic fat stranding, and possibly small fluid collections or abscesses. Decreased fatty shadows around the distal colon could be interpreted as edema/inflammation obscuring normal fat planes.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) 2014 Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Treatment of Left-Sided Colonic Diverticulitis recommend antibiotics for acute uncomplicated diverticulitis, especially in patients with systemic signs of infection (e.g., fever, leukocytosis).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Double contrast | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | IV antibiotic | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Control diet | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
