  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, cut it out (for diagnosis)!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Biopsy. A huge ulcer with red, raised edges is highly suspicious for malignancy, such as a Marjolin's ulcer (squamous cell carcinoma arising in a chronic wound) or other aggressive skin cancer. Establishing a definitive diagnosis is the critical first step before initiating any treatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBiopsy is paramount for any suspicious skin lesion, especially a chronic, non-healing ulcer with features like raised or everted edges, which are classic signs of malignancy. A biopsy provides histological confirmation of the diagnosis, allowing for appropriate staging and definitive treatment planning, which could range from surgical excision to radiotherapy or systemic therapy depending on the type and extent of cancer. Without a biopsy, any treatment would be empiric and potentially harmful or ineffective.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Topical steroids) (Incorrect): Steroids can mask underlying malignancy and are inappropriate for an undiagnosed, suspicious ulcer. They might be used for inflammatory conditions, but not for a lesion concerning for cancer.\nOption C (Radiotherapy) (Incorrect): Radiotherapy is a treatment modality for cancer, not a diagnostic tool. It should only be considered after a definitive diagnosis has been established via biopsy.\nOption D (Topical antibiotics) (Incorrect): While an ulcer can be infected, the primary concern with raised edges is malignancy. Topical antibiotics would only address potential infection and would delay the necessary diagnostic workup for cancer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Ulcer Feature | Suspicion | Initial Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| Raised, everted edges, non-healing | Malignancy (e.g., SCC, Marjolin's) | Biopsy |\n| Punched-out, painful, pale base | Arterial insufficiency | ABI, revascularization consult |\n| Irregular, shallow, edematous, hyperpigmented | Venous insufficiency | Compression, duplex ultrasound |\n| Painless, plantar, calloused edges | Neuropathic (diabetic) | Offloading, glycemic control |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Suspicious ulcer? Biopsy first, treat later.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThe question describes a visual finding: 'Picture of a huge ulcer in the leg, the ulcer is red with raised edges.' This appearance is highly suspicious for malignancy, such as a Marjolin's ulcer or other skin cancer, necessitating a diagnostic biopsy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Basal Cell and Squamous Cell Skin Cancers (2023) recommend biopsy for any suspicious skin lesion to establish a definitive diagnosis and guide subsequent management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Topical steroids | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Biopsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Radiotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Topical antibiotics | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
