  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Night pain in the rectum? Think muscle spasm, not just piles!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT - The correct answer is Proctalgia fugax. This diagnosis is strongly suggested by the complaint of sudden, severe rectal pain occurring predominantly at night, often waking the patient from sleep, which is a hallmark symptom of this condition.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nProctalgia fugax is characterized by episodic, severe, cramping pain in the rectum, caused by a spasm of the levator ani muscle or anal sphincter. The pain is typically brief, lasting seconds to minutes, and resolves spontaneously. Its nocturnal predominance is a key diagnostic feature, differentiating it from other causes of rectal discomfort.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Hemorrhoids typically cause pain, bleeding, and itching, but the pain is not characteristically 'mostly at night' or sudden and severe like a spasm. Itching can be present, but the nocturnal pain pattern points away from hemorrhoids as the primary diagnosis.\nOption B (Incorrect): 'Gay bowel syndrome' is an outdated and non-specific term referring to a collection of anorectal conditions, often infectious, seen in homosexual men. It is not a specific diagnosis for rectal pain and itching, and the symptoms described do not directly point to this broad category.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Symptoms | Timing/Duration | Pathophysiology |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Proctalgia Fugax | Sudden, severe, cramping rectal pain | Predominantly nocturnal, brief (seconds-minutes) | Spasm of levator ani or anal sphincter |\n| Hemorrhoids | Pain, bleeding, itching, prolapse | Variable, often exacerbated by defecation | Engorged vascular cushions |\n| Levator Ani Syndrome | Dull, aching, pressure in rectum | Persistent, worse with sitting, relieved by lying down | Chronic tension/spasm of levator ani |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sudden, severe, nocturnal rectal pain that resolves quickly is Proctalgia fugax.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNo specific imaging findings are associated with Proctalgia fugax, as it is a functional disorder. Endoscopy would typically be normal, ruling out out structural causes of pain.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) guidelines for anorectal disorders emphasize ruling out structural pathology for chronic or recurrent rectal pain.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hemorrhoids | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Gay bowel syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Proctalgia fugax | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
