  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the rectum cramps at night, think fugax, not fright!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Proctalgia fugax. This diagnosis perfectly aligns with the patient's presentation of sudden, severe rectal spasms, accompanied by autonomic symptoms like diaphoresis and tachycardia, particularly occurring at night.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nProctalgia fugax is characterized by episodic, intense, cramping rectal pain caused by spasm of the smooth muscle of the anal canal or pelvic floor, specifically the levator ani muscle. Its nocturnal predominance and association with autonomic symptoms (diaphoresis, tachycardia) are classic features, often waking patients from sleep. The pain is typically brief, lasting seconds to minutes, and resolves spontaneously, differentiating it from other causes of chronic or constant rectal pain.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Thrombosed hemorrhoid) (Incorrect): While painful, a thrombosed hemorrhoid typically presents with constant, severe pain and a palpable, tender perianal mass, not episodic spasms. Systemic symptoms like diaphoresis and tachycardia are not primary features, nor is a nocturnal predilection.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Proctalgia Fugax | Levator Ani Syndrome | Thrombosed Hemorrhoid | Anal Fissure |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Pain Character** | Sudden, severe, episodic spasm/cramp | Dull ache, pressure, constant | Constant, severe, throbbing | Sharp, tearing, especially with defecation |\n| **Timing** | Nocturnal, wakes patient | Worse with sitting, prolonged standing | Constant | Post-defecation, can persist |\n| **Associated Symptoms** | Diaphoresis, tachycardia | Tenesmus, difficulty sitting | Palpable lump, swelling | Bleeding, sentinel tag |\n| **Duration** | Seconds to minutes | Hours to days | Days to weeks | Weeks to months |\n| **Etiology** | Smooth muscle spasm | Pelvic floor muscle spasm/tension | Clot in external hemorrhoidal vein | Tear in anoderm |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Nocturnal rectal spasms with autonomic symptoms point to proctalgia fugax.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPhysical examination and imaging are typically normal in Proctalgia fugax, as it is a functional disorder. No specific findings on proctoscopy or imaging studies would confirm the diagnosis, which is made clinically by history.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Functional Anorectal Pain (2021). These guidelines emphasize a comprehensive history and physical examination to exclude organic pathology, and recommend conservative management for functional anorectal pain syndromes like proctalgia fugax.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Thrombosed hemorrhoid | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Proctalgia fugax | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 467344482-General-Surgery-MCQ-Saudi (1).pdf**\n",
